Sets the maximum allowed mono heap size in bytes that can be used when garbage collection is disabled.When garbage collection is disabled the mono heap will always grow as needed when scripts allocate memory until the heap size exceeds that specified by gcDisableMaxHeapSize.You should set this value to a sensible number for your application, for example 16MB.

Gets or sets the garbage collector enabled state.PSVita.Utility.gcEnable can be used to disable or enable garbage collection.IMPORTANT. This option must be used with great care and only in applications which already have very tight control of their allocations and wish to eliminate any remaining hard to fix GC stalls during game-play.When disabled the application must manually call System.GC.Collect at appropriate points, i.e. some natural break in game-play. Before calling System.GC.Collect you must first re-enable GC. You should also ensure that GC is enabled while loading levels.When disabled the mono heap will always grow as needed when scripts allocate memory until the heap size exceeds that specified by PSVita.Utility.gcDisableMaxHeapSize.When the maximum heap size has been exceeded GC is automatically turned back on and cannot then be disabled.A typical usage pattern is show below.
